column3: Thirty seven sites in Chicago, sampled over four seasons
column6: 6-8 hour period of sampling, with flow rate of 0.4 m3 per min
column15: NR
column17: "The method detection limit (MDL) was determined for each congener and calculated as three times the standard deviation of the congener mass in the field blank (n = 14) plus the minimum peak response. The congener MDL ranged from 0.1 ng per sample to 2.2 ng per sample. When the typical air volume of 200 m3 was applied, the congener MDL ranged from 0.5 to 11 pg/m3...Samples were not corrected for surrogate recoveries or blanks."

column3: Fifty samples collected per site over all four seasons
column6: "Average air volumes collected were 277±15 m3 and 191±60 m3 for BUTAL and Mudanya, respectively"
column15: plastic "The filters and PUFs were wrapped in aluminum foil and brought to the laboratory in airtight plastic bags."
column17: "The limit of detection (LOD) value was obtained by taking the average of each PCB level (ng) measured in the blank samples and adding the standard deviation multiplied by 3 (LOD=avg.+3×SD). If the PCB congeners were greater than the LOD values in the samples, these were reported in the calculations. Furthermore, each sample was subjected to blank sample correction."

column3: Uludag University - samples collected over all four seasons
column6: "Average air volumes collected were 165 ± 62.1 and 287 ± 22.5 for Uludag University and Yavuzselim sampling sites, respectively. Sampling volumes showed variability depending on sampling periods and loss of pressure."
column15: "PUFs were then covered with aluminum foil and transferred in jars to sampling sites...Samples that were ready for chromatographic analysis after the processes of extraction, volume reduction, and fractionation were kept in a deep freeze of -20oC."
column17: "The limit of detection (LOD) for every PCB congener was determined by adding three standard deviation (average + 3 SD) to the average of the blanks. column3: samples taken from multiple rooms in a single building ("PCB contamination in the indoor air was measured in 35 office rooms that were frequented by the participants. Indoor air measurements were planned and carried out according to guidelines DIN EN ISO 16000-12 and DIN ISO 16000-13.1")
column6: "Air sampling...was performed with the sorbent tube XAD 2 type Orbo 42sTM. The sorbent tube was connected to the pumping units (total volume inaccuracy ± 5%; flow rate constancy ± 2%) adjusted to a flow rate of 2 L/min and a sampling time of approximately 8 h. Total sample volumes were within the limits of 0.8-1.0 m³." AND "Furthermore, the 6 marker congeners (PCB 28, PCB 52, PCB 101, PCB 138, PCB 153, and PCB 180) were analyzed. The pumping units (total volume inaccuracy ± 5%; flow rate constancy ± 2%) were connected to sampling modules with filters and sorbent tubes consisting of polyurethane (PU) foam spiked with 13C12-labeled PCB standards. For air sampling, the pumping units were adjusted to a flow volume of 2.7 m³ per hour and a sampling time of 2 h (total sample volumes ranged from 5.2 to 5.5 m³)."

column17: "The limit of quantification (LOQ) was between 1.0 and 2.0 ng/mL for the individual PCB congeners, resulting in LOQs between 0.2 and 2 ng/m3 for measured PCBs."

column3: "A soil fugacity sampler coupled to an ambient air sampler was deployed during five consecutive days on the soil near Resolute Lake during summer 2016 (Figure S5 and Table S1 for details)."
column6: Storage conditions and temperature were described in HERO #2151511.
column15: Described in HERO #2151511: "After sampling, air and soil samples were stored in freezers at -20 C until analysis."
column17: "Method detection limits (MDLs) of PCBs and OCPs were determined as 3 times the standard deviation (SD) of method blank concentrations. MDLs were derived from the lowest standard in the calibration curve for those PCBs with no signals in the blanks. MDLs were in the range from 0.05 to 0.72 pg/m3 for soil/ambient air fugacity measurements."

column3: "PM2.5 sampling was conducted in four sites in Gwangju, Korea from December 2017 to March 2018."
column15: "The collected PM2.5 samples were wrapped with pre-heated aluminum foils (at 550° for 6 h) and stored -20° until analysis."
column17: "Method detection limit (MDL) is defined as the lowest concentration of analytes that can be distinguished from the method blank and can be reported with 99% confidence...For determining MDL, low concentration of the analytes with good recovery was spiked in seven blank filters and the standard deviation of the concentration for each analyte was obtained through the analysis of standard spiked filter. MDL was calculated by multiplying the obtained standard deviation by 3.14 (Students t value for a 99% confidence interval for 7 replicates). Limit of quantification (LOQ) is the lowest concentration of analytes that can be distinguished from MDL and quantified. LOQ was estimated as ten times the standard deviation of analyzed concentration."

column3: "We selected two types of sampling sites, source sites and nonsource sites. Source sites were close to areas with various industrial activities...e-waste dismantling...Samples from nonsource sites presented general PCB profile in urban, rural, and remote sites. All the site information and sampling periods are detailed in Table S1. In summary, PUF-PAS sets were deployed at 62 sampling sites across China for three cycles in autumn and winter of 2016 and summer of 2017."
column15: "All samples were delivered back to the lab and stored at ?20 °C before analysis."
column17: "The method detection limits (MDLs) were assigned as the total of average values of field blanks and three times their standard deviations. MDLs were calculated as three times the instrumental detection limits (IDLs) and reported if a congener was not detected in field and procedural blanks. IDLs were defined as the amounts of analytes generating a signal-to-noise of 3:1 using the lowest standard concentration, assuming a linear increase of response. The IDLs and MDLs of 209 PCB congeners were in ranges of 0.2?470 pg and 0.002?16 pg/m3 and are presented in Table S4."

column17: "The limits of quantification (LOQs) were defined as the mean concentration of field or procedural blanks (using always the more restrictive of the two) plus three times the standard deviation of the blank response. column3: "Ten (10) sampling locations were selected for deploying Polyurethane Foam Passive Air Samplers (PUF-PAS). The study area (Punjab Province) was divided into two zones: an industrial zone, including highly populated industrialized cities such as Faisalabad, Sheikhupura and Lahore (the provincial capital), and an agricultural zone, including the cotton-growing areas of Pakistan (Fig. 1). Five PAS were deployed on the roofs of one-floor buildings in five locations in the industrial zone: Faisalabad (FSD), Sheikhupura (SHK), Shahdra (SHR), Lahore (LHR) and Phool Nagar (PN). Five more PAS were deployed on the roofs of one-floor houses in various locations in the agricultural zone: Sahiwal (SHW), Cheechawatni (CHW), Mianchanu (MCH), Khanewal (KHW) and Kabirwala (KBW). Locations of each sampling site are given in the Supplementary data in Table A1."
column15: glass
column17: "Measurements less than the IDLs were considered as not detected (ND)."

column3: "The monitoring space for this study was designed along that utilized by Jaward et al., 2005. Deployment points extended between latitude 1845N and longitude 102145E."

column3: "The sampling site, shown in Figure S1, is located near Pigeon Lake, at the James McLean Oliver Ecological Centre (JMOEC) (44° 33? N, 78° 30? W), which is about 25 km NNW of Peterborough, Ontario, Canada. The 110-hectare rural waterfront property consists of lake shoreline, pastures, marshland, and forested habitat. The research site is representative of the mostly rural nature of southern Ontario and has no industrial sources within 25 km...Thirty-six air samples were taken at 2-hour intervals...over an intensive three day sampling period in early spring...Sampling began at noon on April 24, 2000, with samples being collected serially at 2-hour intervals over a three-day period, finishing at noon on April 27, 2000."
column15: "The plugs were then stored in solvent-rinsed glass jars with aluminum-lined lids. Clean PUF plugs and GMFs were loaded, using solvent-rinsed tongs, into sampler modules prior to sampling. After sampling, the sample modules were unloaded and immediately rinsed with solvent, and the PUF plugs and GMFs were replaced in the original sample jars and frozen at < ?5 °C.

column3: "All samples were collected at Tudor Hill on the west coast of Bermuda between May 1992 and July 1993. A 23-m sampling tower, owned by AEROCE (the Atmosphere-Ocean Chemistry Experiment), is located at this site, approximately 50 m in from the shore. Our sampler was mounted on the north side of this tower."
column15: "After the sample was collected, the sampler head was again brought into the clean room, the glass fiber filter and PUF plug were wrapped in their original aluminum foil, the PUF plug was placed in its aluminum can (which was again sealed with black plastic tape), and the sample was stored in a freezer."
column17: "A total of 34 samples were collected. Of these, three had PCB concentrations which were at or below the detection limit. We did not include these samples in our data analysis."

column3: "Sampling was carried out at Egbert, ON, Canada (44'14' N, 79'47' W, 251 masl), in a rural area which is some 100 km north of the city of Toronto. The research site was chosen to be representative of the mostly rural nature of southern Ontario and has no local industrial sources within 15 km...Sampling was started on July 10, 1988. After that date, samples were predominantly taken on a 2-day observational cycle until July 1, 1989. Subsequent to that date, sampling was changed to a 1 day in 6 cycle. Three record gaps (the longest being over 3 weeks) were encountered during the sampling; other than this, the sampling was continuous."
column15: "After sampling, the cartridge was unloaded immediately and the foam plugs were replaced in the original sample jars and refrigerated at either 4 °C or frozen at <-5 °C. The samples were kept stored at low temperature until receipt by the laboratory in Winnipeg, MB, Canada, when they were allowed to rise to room temperature. In the analysis stage at the laboratory, the longest period between warming and analysis was 2 months."
